@node "Introduction" "Introduction to Menu"
@next "Requirements"
@prev "Copyright"

@{JCENTER}@{b}@{u}Introduction@{ub}@{uu}

Yes, this is another program starter. So why release another one ? Is it better,faster,smaller ?
No, not really. It just happens to be mine and it seems to work pretty well.
It doesn't have a lot of options or other flashy bits & pieces like some have.
But because it's programmed with AmosPro, the screen/windows are hidden, so they won't
disturb you while doing something else.

After a lot of years (5-6), I @{u}finally@{uu} decided to release it.
It's running on my Amiga for 10 years now, getting more and more
stable over the years. And I still use it every day :)


@{u}@{b}Note:@{ub}@{uu}

The config file *should* be in S: under the name 'menu3,4.keys' !!!


@endnode

@node "Requirements" "Requirements for Menu"
@next "Options"
@prev "Introduction"

@{JCENTER}@{b}@{u}Requirements@{ub}@{uu}

@{b}Menu@{ub} requires an Amiga with at least @{b}V36@{ub}, @{b}amos.library V2.30 and easylife.library V1.02@{ub}.
You also should have opal/12 in your fonts: drawer.

@endnode

@node "Options" "The Options"
@next "Bugs"
@prev "Requirements"

@{JCENTER}@{b}@{u}Options@{ub}@{uu}
@{JLEFT}
· Pressing Help will show the @{i}HelpZone.@{ui}
· Delete a button - n
· Everything new - Shift n
· Loading a temp file from RAM: - l
· Loading 'DMX..' format - Shift l
· Loading as 'ASCII' format - a
· Saving a temp file to RAM: - s
· Saving as 'DMX93.10' format - Shift d
· Saving as 'DMX94.8' format - Shift a
· Saving as 'DMX95.7' format - Shift s
· String search - z
· String search w/ arrow - Shift z
· Input ALL 90 buttons - Shift m
· Input button 1 to 30 - F1
· Input button 31 to 60 - F2
· Input button 61 to 90 - F3
· Change 1 button - F10
· Start line no. - i
· Quit - Shift q or ESC

· Selecting 'Menu Mouse Off' puts the menu (rougly) under the RMB.
· Selecting the 'about/made by' menuitem, shows you a nice gag ;)


@endnode

@node "Misc" "Misc"
@next "Thanks"
@prev "ToDo"

@{JCENTER}@{b}@{u}Misc@{ub}@{uu}
@{JLEFT}
· If you wanna quit Menu after starting a program, just put -q infront of the pathname.
· If you give in a lot of path/program names, but you want out, just type 'END' or 'EINDE' on the pathname line.
  This will end the input routine.
· Same as above, but type 'NEW' or 'NIEUW', if your (current) program name should be deleted. This will also
  end the input routine.
· Menu344 is the dutch version, Menu344e the english one.
· Under the menu mouse off/on option there's a menuitem that shows the current file format that 'Menu' has loaded.
· Some gags are hidden, please look out for them :)))

@endnode

